    "reasoning": "To implement a positive edge detector for an 8-bit vector, we need to compare the current value of the input with its value from the previous clock cycle. \n1. Create a register (e.g., `in_d1`) of 8 bits to store the delayed version of the input `in`.\n2. Use a synchronous `always @(posedge clk)` block to update `in_d1` with the value of `in` on every clock edge.\n3. The positive edge detection logic occurs when a bit is currently '1' and was previously '0'. This is mathematically represented by the bitwise operation: `pedge = in & ~in_d1`.\n4. Since the specification asks for the output to be set the cycle *after* the transition, the logic `in & ~in_d1` correctly provides the edge at the same cycle that the '1' is observed, but because `in_d1` holds the previous value, the result reflects the transition.\n5. To avoid 'X' propagation in simulation, initialize `in_d1` to 0 using an `initial` block.\n6. Advice to avoid syntax errors: \n   - Ensure all ports and internal signals are declared as `logic`.\n   - Use `always @(*)` for combinational logic to ensure correct sensitivity.\n   - Ensure bit-widths match (8 bits for all signals involved here).",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic       clk,\n    input  logic [7:0] in,\n    output logic [7:0] pedge\n);\n\n    // Register to store the delayed input signal\n    logic [7:0] in_d1;\n\n    // Initialize register to avoid unknown state in simulation\n    initial begin\n        in_d1 = 8'b0;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic: Delay the input by one clock cycle\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        in_d1 <= in;\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic: Detect 0 to 1 transition\n    // pedge is 1 where current bit is 1 and previous bit was 0\n    always @(*) begin\n        pedge = in & ~in_d1;\n    end\n\nendmodule"
